Squaring:

\[
\begin{aligned}
z^{2}+x+y-2 z \sqrt{x+y} & =x+y+2 \sqrt{x y} \\
z^{2}-2 z \sqrt{x+y} & =2 \sqrt{x y}
\end{aligned}
\]

Squaring again:

\[
\begin{gathered}
z^{4}+4 z^{2}(x+y)-4 z^{3} \sqrt{x+y}=4 x y \\
\sqrt{x+y}=\frac{z^{4}+4 z^{2}(x+y)-4 x y}{4 z^{3}}=\frac{1}{4} z+\frac{x+y}{z}-\frac{x y}{z^{3}}
\end{gathered}
\]

Eva is right: if \(z\) were rational, then \(\sqrt{x+y}\) would always have to be rational, which is clearly not possible, because whenever \(x+y\) is not a perfect square, \(\sqrt{x+y}\) is irrational and thus \(z\) is irrational as well. There are infinitely many pairs \((x, y)\) for which \(x+y\) is not a perfect square.

Regarding Rolf's opinion, if we set \(x=\left(n^{2}-1\right)^{2}\) and \(y=4 n^{2}\) with \(n \in \mathbb{N}\), then

\[
z=\left(n^{2}-1\right)+2 n+\sqrt{n^{4}-2 n^{2}+1+4 n^{2}}=n^{2}-1+2 n+n^{2}+1=2 n^{2}+2 n=2 n(n+1)
\]

In this case, \(z\) is always an integer and thus rational. Therefore, there are also infinitely many pairs \((x, y)\) for which \(z\) is rational.

